086–1172","1088–1155":"1088–1155","2 July 1137":"2 July 1137","1137":"1137","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1088":"1088","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne, France":"Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France","Chêne-Bougeries, Geneve, Switzerland":"Chêne-Bougeries, Geneva, Switzerland","Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland":"Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Cuiseaux was born in 1110, in Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France, her father, Pons de Cuiseaux, was 24 and her mother, Laura Senecy, was 22. She had at least 1 son with Amédée de Genève I. She died on 2 July 1137, in Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1110–2 July 1137":"1110–2. juuli 1137","1110–1137":"1110–1137","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1086–1172":"1086–1172","1088–1155":"1088–1155","2 July 1137":"2. juuli 1137","1137":"1137","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1088":"1088","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne, France":"Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","Chêne-Bougeries, Geneve, Switzerland":"Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Šveits","Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland":"Genève, Genève, Šveits"},"fi":{"1110–2 July 1137":"1110–2. heinäkuuta 1137","1110–1137":"1110–1137","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1086–1172":"1086–1172","1088–1155":"1088–1155","2 July 1137":"2. heinäkuuta 1137","1137":"1137","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1088":"1088","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne, France":"Cuiseaux, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Ranska","Chêne-Bougeries, Geneve, Switz